white chooses the square on which the exchange will take place. if left on c4, this cripples white's center pawn structure while isolating the e4 pawn from additional pawn support for at least a move. this creates initiative and momentum loss. allowing the exchange to take place on b3, however, allows white the option of taking with the Q or a2 pawn (opening a R lane), and both maintain center pawn structure integrity.

better is 20....f5. if white takes or does not take, his position is left cramped. since 21.PxP (ep) RxP 22. f5 Bc8 ...white cannot swing his Ns over to the K-side of the board through f3 or the isolated f pawn is lost; or 21.Nef3 g5 22.PxP PxP leaves black with a 2-pawn storm on white's castled K and pieces out of position to properly defend against it.
